WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:02.542
Here's a fun experiment.

00:00:02.542 --> 00:00:05.240
We'll push a repository with a gigabyte

00:00:05.240 --> 00:00:07.553
of data to another machine twice.

00:00:07.553 --> 00:00:09.480
The first push carries everything,

00:00:09.480 --> 00:00:12.178
and the second carries only what changed.

00:00:12.178 --> 00:00:13.335
Watch the numbers,

00:00:13.335 --> 00:00:16.033
the push command prints exactly how much

00:00:16.033 --> 00:00:16.804
it moved.

00:00:17.566 --> 00:00:20.249
The trick is in the setup.

00:00:20.249 --> 00:00:22.037
After the first push,

00:00:22.037 --> 00:00:24.720
the CLI keeps an identical immutable

00:00:24.720 --> 00:00:26.956
base image on both machines.

00:00:26.956 --> 00:00:29.638
The next push compares blocks against

00:00:29.638 --> 00:00:32.321
that base and sends only the

00:00:32.321 --> 00:00:32.768
difference.

00:00:32.768 --> 00:00:33.662
No flags,

00:00:33.662 --> 00:00:34.557
no bookkeeping,

00:00:34.557 --> 00:00:36.792
it's the same push command.

00:00:40.069 --> 00:00:42.636
The first push to another machine carries

00:00:42.636 --> 00:00:43.737
the whole image,

00:00:43.737 --> 00:00:45.937
and the output says it plainly:

00:00:45.937 --> 00:00:47.037
two gigabytes transferred,

00:00:47.037 --> 00:00:47.771
marked full.

00:00:47.771 --> 00:00:49.238
This is the baseline.

00:00:52.238 --> 00:00:54.004
Two gigabytes in forty-four seconds,

00:00:54.004 --> 00:00:54.711
marked full.

00:00:54.711 --> 00:00:57.536
The CLI also kept an identical base on

00:00:57.536 --> 00:00:58.243
both sides;

00:00:58.243 --> 00:01:00.362
that's the setup for the magic.

00:01:03.639 --> 00:01:05.123
Change a little data:

00:01:05.123 --> 00:01:07.348
fifty megabytes out of two gigabytes.

00:01:14.864 --> 00:01:17.058
A small change in a big image.

00:01:20.344 --> 00:01:21.252
Push again.

00:01:21.252 --> 00:01:22.161
Same command,

00:01:22.161 --> 00:01:24.885
but read the output this time:

00:01:24.885 --> 00:01:26.702
about fifty megabytes transferred,

00:01:26.702 --> 00:01:27.610
marked delta,

00:01:27.610 --> 00:01:29.881
against a two gigabyte image.

00:01:29.881 --> 00:01:32.151
Only the changed blocks travelled.

00:01:35.151 --> 00:01:37.309
Fifty megabytes in under six seconds,

00:01:37.309 --> 00:01:39.466
out of a two gigabyte image.

00:01:39.466 --> 00:01:41.264
The numbers are the proof.

00:01:44.550 --> 00:01:46.679
Both machines hold the same repository,

00:01:46.679 --> 00:01:47.743
refreshed in seconds.

00:01:47.743 --> 00:01:50.582
Run it hourly if you like — the

00:01:50.582 --> 00:01:52.001
cost is the change,

00:01:52.001 --> 00:01:53.066
not the size.

00:01:56.066 --> 00:01:58.495
Frequent backups stop being expensive.

00:01:59.321 --> 00:02:01.271
Small changes mean small transfers,

00:02:01.271 --> 00:02:03.221
every time after the first.

00:02:03.221 --> 00:02:05.172
Just one tutorial left now:

00:02:05.172 --> 00:02:07.902
making sure you never run out of

00:02:07.902 --> 00:02:08.292
disk.

00:02:08.292 --> 00:02:10.632
See you in the final one!
